Note:
This file implements the Four-Tier Memory Architecture for v0.0.8.5

TIER 1: STACK - Automatic local variables (compiler-managed, zero-cost)
TIER 2: ARENA - Temporary allocations (bump-pointer, bulk free, O(1))
TIER 3: OWNED HEAP - Permanent structures (individual ownership, explicit free)
TIER 4: SHARED - Reference counted (for shared ownership with atomic operations)

GOLDEN RULE: "Arena for TEMPS, Ownership for PERMANENT"

This architecture was proven in v0.0.8.4.5.2 to reduce memory leaks by 34.6%
while maintaining compilation correctness.

Depends on:
- assembly/syscall.runa (for mmap/munmap/brk)
- core/memory_core.runa (for memory operations)
- core/alignment_core.runa (for alignment)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/alignment_core.runa" as Alignment
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation Method Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant ALLOC_METHOD_BRK as Integer is 1      Note: brk/sbrk allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP as Integer is 2     Note: mmap allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED as Integer is 3   Note: Shared/reference-counted allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_ARENA as Integer is 4    Note: Arena allocation

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ASan-CLASS CANARY / GUARD PROTOCOL
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
ASan-class canary / guard protocol (production-debug builds only).

DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED gates the entire protocol. When set to 0,
every canary/quarantine code path is wrapped in an If-guard and skipped,
restoring the B2-canonical 32-byte owned-heap header and 48-byte shared
header layouts and the original brk-free-list / munmap deallocation paths.

When set to 1, the allocator installs:
 1) A 16-byte pre-buffer canary (two 8-byte words) IMMEDIATELY AFTER the
    canonical 32-byte header fields (offsets 32 and 40 within the
    expanded 48-byte owned header). The canary words are derived from
    the allocation_id via a deterministic mix so every allocation has a
    UNIQUE canary value - an attacker who reads one freed block cannot
    forge the canary for another block. This is strictly stronger than
    ASan, which uses a fixed magic byte.
 2) A 16-byte post-buffer canary (two 8-byte words) at ptr+aligned_size.
    Same per-allocation derivation.
 3) Verification on deallocate() and on free-list reuse in allocate(): a
    mismatch aborts the process via canary_fail_abort with a fixed-format
    diagnostic on stderr (fd 2) and exit code 134 (matches ASan).
 4) Quarantine on free: a 64-entry FIFO ring of recently-freed blocks
    whose user buffers are poisoned with a per-allocation pattern. The
    quarantine delays reuse so use-after-free reads observe obvious bad
    data instead of stale-but-plausible data. Eviction-time canary
    re-check catches corruption that occurred WHILE the block was in
    quarantine.
 5) Generation-aware validation: the existing registry generation
    counter is verified at allocate-time reuse so dangling references
    that survived across a reuse cycle are caught.

OUT OF SCOPE for v0.0.8.5 (documented in DEV-LOGS/C5-canary-protocol.md):
 - mprotect guard pages (requires new syscall wrapper - v0.0.8.7).
 - Tagged pointers (requires compiler pass - v0.1.0).
 - Shadow memory (requires load/store instrumentation - v0.0.9.x).
:End Note

Constant DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED as Integer is 1

Note: Header / canary sizes.
Note: ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE is the canonical 32-byte field block (B2
Note: invariant: allocation_id @ 0, generation @ 8, total_size @ 16,
Note: alloc_type @ 24). Do NOT modify these offsets.
Note: ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE is the pre-buffer canary slot appended
Note: AFTER the canonical block. ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE is the
Note: post-buffer canary appended AFTER the user buffer.
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: Shared-header equivalents (48-byte canonical shared block).
Constant SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as Integer is 48
Constant SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: Canary location identifiers passed to canary_fail_abort for the
Note: diagnostic. Numeric so the message formatter can emit a fixed token.
Constant CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED as Integer is 1
Constant CANARY_LOC_POST_OWNED as Integer is 2
Constant CANARY_LOC_PRE_SHARED as Integer is 3
Constant CANARY_LOC_POST_SHARED as Integer is 4
Constant CANARY_LOC_QUARANTINE_EVICT as Integer is 5

Note: Per-allocation canary seed mixers. The seed is derived from
Note: allocation_id and generation via two odd 64-bit multipliers and an
Note: XOR fold so an attacker who knows the constants AND knows the
Note: allocation_id+generation can predict the canary - but not without
Note: BOTH. The multipliers are odd primes chosen to fit in signed 64-bit
Note: (the Runa lexer parses signed 64-bit integer literals) with good
Note: avalanche when mixed via multiply-xor-multiply.
Note: MULT_A = 8000000000000000029 (odd, in signed-64 range, near 2^63 max)
Note: MULT_B = 6364136223846793005 (Knuth's LCG multiplier, well-known good)
Note: XOR_A  = 7256775408644581463 (large odd prime)
Note: XOR_B  = 9043521260105129019 - this exceeds signed-64 range, so
Note: replaced with 5871781006564002453 (large odd prime in range).
Constant CANARY_SEED_MULT_A as Integer is 8000000000000000029
Constant CANARY_SEED_MULT_B as Integer is 6364136223846793005
Constant CANARY_SEED_XOR_A as Integer is 7256775408644581463
Constant CANARY_SEED_XOR_B as Integer is 5871781006564002453

Note: Poison byte pattern written to freed user buffers in quarantine.
Note: A recognizable bit pattern. Chosen so a use-after-free pointer
Note: dereferenced as an Integer reads as an obvious sentinel during
Note: debugging. Original 0xDEADBEEFDEADBEEF exceeds signed-64 range, so
Note: replaced with 0x5EADBEEF5EADBEEF = 6822018388419498223 (same
Note: visual pattern minus the leading 'D' nibble) which stays in range.
Constant CANARY_POISON_WORD as Integer is 6822018388419498223

Note: Quarantine capacity. 64 entries x (8 user_ptr + 8 total_size +
Note: 8 alloc_id + 8 alloc_type) = 32 bytes per entry x 64 = 2048 bytes.
Note: Lazy-allocated via mmap so we do not consume memory unless debug
Note: is on AND a deallocate has actually fired.
Constant QUARANTINE_CAPACITY as Integer is 64
Constant QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 32

Let quarantine_table be 0           Note: mmap-backed quarantine ring buffer (lazy init)
Let quarantine_head be 0            Note: Next slot to write
Let quarantine_count be 0           Note: Number of occupied slots (<= QUARANTINE_CAPACITY)
Let quarantine_initialized be 0     Note: 1 once quarantine_table mmap'd

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ALLOCATION REGISTRY - Internal allocation tracking for borrow validation
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
This registry tracks all live allocations to enable runtime borrow lifetime validation.
It detects use-after-free, use-after-realloc, and out-of-bounds access.

Registry Entry Structure (56 bytes):
  offset 0:  is_occupied (1=occupied, 0=empty, 8 bytes)
  offset 8:  allocation_id (unique ID, 8 bytes)
  offset 16: generation (incremented on reuse, 8 bytes)
  offset 24: base_ptr (user data pointer, 8 bytes)
  offset 32: size (allocation size in bytes, 8 bytes)
  offset 40: alloc_type (1=brk, 2=mmap, 3=shared, 8 bytes)
  offset 48: is_alive (1=allocated, 0=freed, 8 bytes)
:End Note

Let registry_table be 0           Note: Pointer to RegistryEntry array
Let registry_capacity be 0        Note: Total slots in hash table
Let registry_count be 0           Note: Number of occupied slots
Let next_allocation_id be 1       Note: Global allocation ID counter (starts at 1)
Let registry_initialized be 0     Note: 1 if registry has been initialized

Let REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY be 1024     Note: Initial number of slots
Let REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE be 56             Note: Size of each RegistryEntry
Let REGISTRY_LOAD_FACTOR_PERCENT be 75    Note: Resize at 75% full

Process called "registry_init" returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize allocation registry with initial capacity
    If registry_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1  Note: Already initialized
    End If

    Let total_size be REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let prot be 3   Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
    Let flags be 34 Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
    Let table_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If table_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0  Note: mmap failed
    End If

    proc memory_fill from Memory with table_ptr, 0, total_size

    Set registry_table to table_ptr
    Set registry_capacity to REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    Set registry_count to 0
    Set next_allocation_id to 1
    Set registry_initialized to 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_ensure_initialized" returns Integer:
    If registry_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return proc registry_init
End Process

Process called "registry_hash" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let index be alloc_id modulo by registry_capacity
    Return index
End Process

Process called "registry_lookup" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let init_check be proc registry_ensure_initialized
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let start_index be proc registry_hash with alloc_id
    Let current_index be start_index
    Let max_probes be registry_capacity
    Let probe_count be 0

    While probe_count is less than max_probes:
        Let entry_offset be current_index multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let entry_ptr be registry_table plus entry_offset
        Let is_occupied be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0

        If is_occupied is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let stored_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 8
        If stored_id is equal to alloc_id:
            Return entry_ptr
        End If

        Set current_index to current_index plus 1
        If current_index is greater than or equal to registry_capacity:
            Set current_index to 0
        End If
        Set probe_count to probe_count plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "registry_insert" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer, base_ptr as Integer, size as Integer, alloc_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let init_check be proc registry_ensure_initialized
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let threshold be registry_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_LOAD_FACTOR_PERCENT
    Set threshold to threshold divided by 100

    If registry_count is greater than or equal to threshold:
        Let resize_result be proc registry_resize
        If resize_result is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let start_index be proc registry_hash with alloc_id
    Let current_index be start_index
    Let max_probes be registry_capacity
    Let probe_count be 0

    While probe_count is less than max_probes:
        Let entry_offset be current_index multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let entry_ptr be registry_table plus entry_offset
        Let is_occupied be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0

        If is_occupied is equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0, 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 8, alloc_id
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16, generation
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 24, base_ptr
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 32, size
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 40, alloc_type
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 48, 1
            Set registry_count to registry_count plus 1
            Return 1
        End If

        Set current_index to current_index plus 1
        If current_index is greater than or equal to registry_capacity:
            Set current_index to 0
        End If
        Set probe_count to probe_count plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "registry_update_alive" takes alloc_id as Integer, is_alive as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 48, is_alive
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_increment_generation" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let current_gen be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16
    Let new_gen be current_gen plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16, new_gen
    Return new_gen
End Process

Process called "registry_get_generation" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16
End Process

Process called "registry_remove" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0, 0
    Set registry_count to registry_count minus 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_resize" returns Integer:
    Let old_table be registry_table
    Let old_capacity be registry_capacity
    Let new_capacity be old_capacity multiplied by 2
    Let new_size be new_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE

    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let new_table be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, new_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If new_table is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_table, 0, new_size

    Let saved_table be registry_table
    Let saved_capacity be registry_capacity
    Let saved_count be registry_count

    Set registry_table to new_table
    Set registry_capacity to new_capacity
    Set registry_count to 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than saved_capacity:
        Let old_entry_offset be i multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let old_entry_ptr be saved_table plus old_entry_offset
        Let is_occupied be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 0

        If is_occupied is equal to 1:
            Let alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 8
            Let generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 16
            Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 24
            Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 32
            Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 40
            Let is_alive be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 48

            Let insert_result be proc registry_insert with alloc_id, generation, base_ptr, size, alloc_type

            If insert_result is equal to 0:
                proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with new_table, new_size
                Set registry_table to saved_table
                Set registry_capacity to saved_capacity
                Set registry_count to saved_count
                Return 0
            End If

            Let new_entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
            If new_entry_ptr is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_entry_ptr, 48, is_alive
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let old_size be saved_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with saved_table, old_size

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_allocate_id" returns Integer:
    Let new_id be next_allocation_id
    Set next_allocation_id to next_allocation_id plus 1
    Return new_id
End Process

Process called "registry_get_count" returns Integer:
    Return registry_count
End Process

Process called "registry_get_capacity" returns Integer:
    Return registry_capacity
End Process

Process called "registry_get_load_factor" returns Integer:
    If registry_capacity is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let load be registry_count multiplied by 100
    Set load to load divided by registry_capacity
    Return load
End Process

Process called "registry_is_initialized" returns Integer:
    Return registry_initialized
End Process

Process called "registry_destroy" returns Integer:
    If registry_initialized is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If registry_table is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let total_size be registry_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with registry_table, total_size
    Set registry_table to 0
    Set registry_capacity to 0
    Set registry_count to 0
    Set registry_initialized to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TIER 2: ARENA ALLOCATOR (Temporary Allocations)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Arena structure (24 bytes):
Note:   offset 0: buffer (pointer to allocated memory)
Note:   offset 8: size (total capacity in bytes)
Note:   offset 16: used (bytes currently allocated)

Process called "arena_create" takes initial_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create arena allocator with initial capacity
    Note: Returns pointer to Arena structure, or 0 on failure

    Note: Allocate arena structure (24 bytes)
    Let arena be proc allocate with 24
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Failed to allocate arena structure
    End If

    Note: Allocate buffer using mmap for large allocations
    Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE = 3
    Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS = 0x22
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34  Note: 0x22
    Let buffer be proc syscall_mmap with 0, initial_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    Note: Check for mmap failure (returns -1 or negative)
    If buffer is less than 0:
        proc deallocate with arena
        Return 0  Note: Failed to allocate buffer
    End If

    Note: Initialize arena fields
    proc memory_set_pointer with arena, 0, buffer      Note: buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 8, initial_size  Note: size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, 0            Note: used = 0

    Return arena
End Process

Process called "arena_allocate" takes arena as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate memory from arena (bump-pointer allocation)
    Note: Returns pointer to allocated memory, or 0 if out of space

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Invalid arena
    End If

    Note: Align allocation size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8

    Note: Get current state
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_pointer with arena, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8
    Let used be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 16

    Note: Check if we have enough space
    Let new_used be used plus aligned_size
    If new_used is greater than capacity:
        Return 0  Note: Out of arena space
    End If

    Note: Calculate allocation address
    Let ptr be buffer plus used

    Note: Update used counter (bump the pointer)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, new_used

    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "arena_string_duplicate" takes arena as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Duplicate string into arena memory
    Note: Used for temporary strings during compilation

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len be proc string_length with str
    Let size be len plus 1  Note: Include null terminator

    Let new_str be proc arena_allocate with arena, size
    If new_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Arena out of space
    End If

    proc memory_copy with new_str, str, size
    Return new_str
End Process

Process called "arena_integer_to_string" takes arena as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert integer to string using arena
    Note: Eliminates temporary string leaks

    Note: Use heap version first, then copy to arena
    Let heap_str be proc integer_to_string with value
    Let arena_str be proc arena_string_duplicate with arena, heap_str
    proc deallocate with heap_str

    Return arena_str
End Process

Process called "arena_string_concat" takes arena as Integer, str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Concatenate strings using arena
    Note: Eliminates result leak

    Let heap_result be proc string_concat with str1, str2
    Let arena_result be proc arena_string_duplicate with arena, heap_result
    proc deallocate with heap_result

    Return arena_result
End Process

Process called "arena_reset" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reset arena to empty state (reuse buffer)
    Note: All previous allocations become invalid!

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, 0  Note: Reset used to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "arena_destroy" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy arena and free all memory
    Note: This is O(1) bulk deallocation!

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc memory_get_pointer with arena, 0
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8

    Note: Unmap the buffer
    If buffer is not equal to 0:
        proc syscall_munmap with buffer, size
    End If

    Note: Free arena structure
    proc deallocate with arena

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "arena_get_used" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get bytes currently used in arena
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 16
End Process

Process called "arena_get_capacity" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get total capacity of arena
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8
End Process

Note: 
============================================================================
TIER 3: OWNED HEAP (Permanent Allocations)
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
Owned-heap allocation header (32 bytes, prepended to every owned
allocation, present at ptr - 32 where ptr is the user-data pointer
returned by allocate()):
  offset -32: allocation_id (unique id assigned via registry_allocate_id, 8 bytes)
  offset -24: generation     (incremented on reuse for use-after-free detection, 8 bytes)
  offset -16: total_size     (header + aligned_user_size, 8 bytes)
  offset -8:  alloc_type     (1=brk, 2=mmap, 8 bytes)
  offset 0:   user data begins here
deallocate() must read these offsets back exactly as allocate() wrote
them; the offset constants in both routines are a single source of
truth and changing one without the other corrupts every owned-heap
free in the system.
:End Note

Note:
Free List Structure (for brk-backed allocations):
When a brk block is freed via deallocate(), we reuse its user data area
to store free-list bookkeeping:
  offset 0: next_free (pointer to next free block in LIFO list, 8 bytes)
  offset 8: is_free   (1=free, 0=allocated, 8 bytes)
The 32-byte allocation header at offset -32..-1 remains intact with its
allocation_id, generation, size, and type values, so registry lookups
for borrows still resolve correctly while the block is parked on the
free list.
:End Note

Note: 
Free List Head (stored in heap metadata):
We reserve the first 16 bytes of the heap for metadata
offset 0: free_list_head (pointer to first free block)
offset 8: heap_initialized (1 if initialized, 0 otherwise)
:End Note

Let heap_metadata_addr be 0  Note: Will be initialized on first brk call

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Free List Management Functions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "heap_init" returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize heap metadata on first brk allocation
    Note: Reserves 16 bytes at the start of the heap for free list metadata

    If heap_metadata_addr is not equal to 0:
        Return heap_metadata_addr  Note: Already initialized
    End If

    Note: Get current brk (this will be our metadata location)
    Let current_brk be proc syscall_brk with 0
    Set heap_metadata_addr to current_brk

    Note: Reserve 16 bytes for metadata
    Let metadata_size be 16
    Let new_brk be current_brk plus metadata_size
    Let result_brk be proc syscall_brk with new_brk

    If result_brk is less than new_brk:
        Set heap_metadata_addr to 0
        Return 0  Note: Failed to reserve metadata space
    End If

    Note: Initialize metadata
    proc memory_set_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0, 0  Note: free_list_head = NULL
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with heap_metadata_addr, 8, 1     Note: heap_initialized = 1

    Return heap_metadata_addr
End Process

Process called "heap_get_free_list_head" returns Integer:
    Note: Get pointer to the first free block
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0
End Process

Process called "heap_set_free_list_head" takes head as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set the free list head pointer
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Let dummy be proc heap_init
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0, head
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_list_find_fit" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find a free block that fits the requested size (first-fit algorithm)
    Note: Returns pointer to user data area, or 0 if no fit found

    Let current be proc heap_get_free_list_head

    While current is not equal to 0:
        Let block_size be proc free_block_get_size with current
        If block_size is greater than or equal to size:
            Return current  Note: Found a fit
        End If
        Set current to proc free_block_get_next with current
    End While

    Return 0  Note: No suitable block found
End Process

Process called "free_list_remove_block" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Remove block from free list (when reusing it for allocation)

    Let head be proc heap_get_free_list_head
    Let next be 0  Note: Declare once at function scope

    Note: If it's the head, update head pointer
    If block is equal to head:
        Set next to proc free_block_get_next with block
        Let dummy be proc heap_set_free_list_head with next
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Search for block in the list
    Let current be head
    While current is not equal to 0:
        Set next to proc free_block_get_next with current
        If next is equal to block:
            Note: Found it - unlink from list
            Let next_next be proc free_block_get_next with block
            Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_next with current, next_next
            Return 1
        End If
        Set current to next
    End While

    Return 0  Note: Block not found in list
End Process

Process called "free_list_add_block" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add block to the front of free list (LIFO)

    Let old_head be proc heap_get_free_list_head
    Let dummy be proc free_block_set_next with block, old_head
    Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_free_flag with block, 1
    Let dummy3 be proc heap_set_free_list_head with block
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_set_next" takes block as Integer, next as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set next pointer in a free block (block points to user data area)
    proc memory_set_pointer with block, 0, next
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_next" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next pointer from a free block
    Return proc memory_get_pointer with block, 0
End Process

Process called "free_block_set_free_flag" takes block as Integer, is_free as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Mark block as free (1) or allocated (0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, 8, is_free
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_free_flag" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if block is free
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with block, 8
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_size" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the total_size field (header + aligned user bytes) for a
    block that is currently parked on the brk free list. The block
    pointer is the user-data address - the same pointer that allocate()
    handed out before the block was freed - so the size field lives at
    block - 32 + 16 = block - 16 in absolute terms. Earlier revisions of
    this routine computed that offset implicitly by using a 16-byte
    base; the math worked but obscured the fact that the header is
    32 bytes. This version names the header size and offset explicitly
    so the relationship to allocate()/deallocate() is auditable.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Subtract the 32-byte header size from the user-data pointer to
       get header_ptr.
    2. Read total_size at offset 16 of the header.
    @End Implementation

    Let header_size be 32
    Let header_ptr be block minus header_size
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CANARY / QUARANTINE HELPERS (ASan-class protocol)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "canary_seed_word_a" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Derives the first per-allocation canary word from (alloc_id, generation).
    Uses a SplitMix64-style mix: multiply by an odd 64-bit constant, XOR
    with another constant, multiply again. The output has good avalanche
    properties across consecutive allocation_ids so canaries for
    neighboring allocations look uncorrelated. An attacker who reads ONE
    freed block's canary cannot predict the canary of another block
    without also knowing its allocation_id+generation, which lives in
    the registry, not in user-controllable memory.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Steps:
     1. Compute mixed = alloc_id * CANARY_SEED_MULT_A.
     2. XOR with generation.
     3. XOR with CANARY_SEED_XOR_A.
     4. Multiply by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B and return.
    All arithmetic is 64-bit signed in Runa; overflow is the normal
    mixing behavior we want and is well-defined wraparound on x86_64.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three integer multiplies and two XORs. Approximately 4 ns on a
    modern x86_64 core. Called twice per allocate/deallocate (pre +
    post canary). With DEBUG=0 the canary call sites are guarded so
    this routine is never invoked in release builds.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The canary is NOT a cryptographic MAC - an attacker who can read
    process memory can recover both seed multipliers and forge the
    canary for any (alloc_id, generation) pair. The protection is
    against UNINTENTIONAL corruption (buffer overrun, use-after-free
    that writes the wrong bytes), not against a memory-disclosure
    adversary. For that, escalate to a process-startup-random seed
    XOR'd in - left as a v0.0.9.x hardening pass.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mixed be alloc_id multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_A
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor generation
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor CANARY_SEED_XOR_A
    Set mixed to mixed multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B
    Return mixed
End Process

Process called "canary_seed_word_b" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Derives the second per-allocation canary word from (alloc_id, generation).
    Uses different mix constants from canary_seed_word_a so the two
    words in a 16-byte canary pair are independent: corrupting both
    requires guessing two 64-bit values, not one.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Same SplitMix64-style mix as canary_seed_word_a but with arguments
    swapped (generation first, then alloc_id) and the CANARY_SEED_XOR_B
    constant instead of A. The asymmetry guarantees word_a != word_b for
    every allocation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as canary_seed_word_a. DEBUG=0 elides via guard.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as canary_seed_word_a: best-effort against unintentional
    corruption; not a cryptographic boundary.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mixed be generation multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_A
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor alloc_id
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor CANARY_SEED_XOR_B
    Set mixed to mixed multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B
    Return mixed
End Process

Process called "canary_write_redzone" takes redzone_ptr as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes the 16-byte canary pair (two 8-byte words) at redzone_ptr.
    Used for both the pre-buffer redzone (inside the expanded header at
    header_ptr + 32) and the post-buffer redzone (at ptr + aligned_size).
    The two words are derived from the same (alloc_id, generation)
    inputs so the pre and post canaries match - a corruption that
    happens to overwrite both pre and post identically (e.g., a wild
    memset) is still detectable because the corrupted bytes will not
    derive correctly from the registry-tracked allocation_id.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute word_a via canary_seed_word_a(alloc_id, generation).
    2. Compute word_b via canary_seed_word_b(alloc_id, generation).
    3. memory_set_int64(redzone_ptr, 0, word_a).
    4. memory_set_int64(redzone_ptr, 8, word_b).
    The caller is responsible for ensuring redzone_ptr points at 16
    bytes the allocator owns; passing a foreign pointer here corrupts
    16 bytes silently.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two integer mixes + two 64-bit stores. About 10 ns on a modern
    core. Called twice per allocate (pre + post). DEBUG=0 elides at
    call sites.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes 16 bytes at redzone_ptr. The caller must verify ownership;
    layout.runa always passes addresses inside its own brk/mmap'd
    regions, so misuse from external callers is structurally
    prevented (this Process is module-private in intent though not in
    visibility).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let word_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
    Let word_b be proc canary_seed_word_b with alloc_id, generation
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 0, word_a
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 8, word_b
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_verify_redzone" takes redzone_ptr as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Verifies the 16-byte canary at redzone_ptr matches the expected
    value derived from (alloc_id, generation). Returns 1 on match, 0 on
    mismatch. Callers that detect a mismatch should abort via
    canary_fail_abort (which writes a fixed-format diagnostic to
    stderr and exits 134, mirroring ASan).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Read stored_word_a at redzone_ptr+0.
    2. Read stored_word_b at redzone_ptr+8.
    3. Recompute expected_word_a, expected_word_b via the mix.
    4. Compare. If EITHER mismatches, return 0. Otherwise return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + two mixes + two compares. ~12 ns. Called twice per
    deallocate (pre + post) and twice per brk-reuse allocate. DEBUG=0
    elides at call sites.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The verifier reads 16 bytes at redzone_ptr; the caller must
    guarantee those bytes are inside the allocator's owned regions.
    A successful verify proves the canary slot was not overwritten
    by a buffer overrun OR by a use-after-free write that happened to
    miss the slot - but does NOT prove the user buffer is uncorrupted
    (the middle of the buffer is not canary-protected, that requires
    shadow memory which is out of scope).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let stored_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 0
    Let stored_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 8
    Let expected_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
    Let expected_b be proc canary_seed_word_b with alloc_id, generation
    If stored_a is not equal to expected_a:
        Return 0
    End If
    If stored_b is not equal to expected_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_poison_buffer" takes buffer_ptr as Integer, size_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Overwrites a freed user buffer with CANARY_POISON_WORD repeated. A
    pointer that survives across the free (use-after-free) and is read
    later as an Integer will return CANARY_POISON_WORD (0xDEADBEEFDEADBEEF),
    which is an obvious sentinel during debugging. Use-after-free
    writes through the dangling pointer are detected at the next
    canary verify if they happen to clobber the post-buffer canary;
    writes to the middle of the buffer are NOT detected here (that
    needs shadow memory). The poison is therefore a partial-protection
    layer that improves diagnosability without claiming completeness.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute word_count = size_bytes / 8 (truncating; the buffer is
       8-byte aligned by aligned_size logic).
    2. Loop i in [0, word_count): memory_set_int64(buffer_ptr, i*8,
       CANARY_POISON_WORD).
    Any trailing bytes (size_bytes mod 8) are not poisoned. In
    practice aligned_size is always a multiple of 8 so the tail is
    empty.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(size / 8) stores. For a 1024-byte allocation this is 128 stores
    ~= 80 ns. The cost scales with allocation size so we only do this
    in DEBUG=1. A vectorized memory_fill could halve the cost but is
    out of scope for v0.0.8.5.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes size_bytes at buffer_ptr. Caller must guarantee buffer_ptr
    is the user pointer of a block currently owned by the allocator
    and that size_bytes does not exceed aligned_size for that block.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size_bytes is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let word_count be size_bytes divided by 8
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than word_count:
        Let byte_offset be i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer_ptr, byte_offset, CANARY_POISON_WORD
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_emit_hex_word" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a 16-character lowercase hex representation of value to fd 2
    (stderr) followed by no separator. Used by canary_fail_abort to
    format the expected/got canary words in the diagnostic message.
    Inlined to one 18-byte stack buffer (16 hex + 2-char "0x" prefix)
    so the diagnostic does not allocate during a failure path.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate a 18-byte stack buffer via repeated memory_set_byte on
       a small mmap'd scratch region (we cannot use a true stack buffer
       in pure-Runa primitives; instead we pre-create a 32-byte
       mmap-backed scratch the first time and reuse it).
    2. Write the "0x" prefix.
    3. For i in [0, 16): extract the (15-i)th nibble of value (most
       significant nibble first), translate to ASCII hex character,
       store at buffer+2+i.
    4. syscall_write(fd=2, buf, 18).
    The scratch buffer is module-statically located via a Let; lazy
    init on first use. After the program crashes via syscall_exit,
    the scratch is reclaimed by the OS.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Failure-path only. Never on the hot path. Cost is irrelevant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes to a private 32-byte mmap'd region the allocator owns and
    to fd 2. No attacker-controlled paths.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let scratch be proc canary_get_diag_scratch
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 48   Note: '0'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 120  Note: 'x'
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let shift_amount be 15 minus i
        Set shift_amount to shift_amount multiplied by 4
        Let nibble be value shifted right by shift_amount
        Set nibble to nibble bitwise and 15
        Let char_code be 0
        If nibble is less than 10:
            Set char_code to nibble plus 48   Note: '0'..'9'
        Otherwise:
            Set char_code to nibble plus 87   Note: 'a'..'f' (97 - 10)
        End If
        Let byte_offset be i plus 2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, byte_offset, char_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 18
    Return 1
End Process

Let canary_diag_scratch_ptr be 0    Note: mmap-backed 32-byte scratch for hex formatting

Process called "canary_get_diag_scratch" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazy-initializes the 32-byte scratch buffer used by
    canary_emit_hex_word for failure diagnostics. Allocated via mmap
    directly (not through allocate) because the failure path must
    function even if the heap is corrupted.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    On first call: mmap a 32-byte page-aligned region with PROT_READ|
    PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS, store the pointer, return
    it. On subsequent calls: return the cached pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path (only fires on canary failure). One-shot mmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 32 bytes outside the regular heap registry. The region
    is never freed - it lives for the process lifetime. Acceptable
    since failure diagnostics are terminal.
    @End Security_Scope

    If canary_diag_scratch_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Return canary_diag_scratch_ptr
    End If
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 32, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set canary_diag_scratch_ptr to ptr
    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "canary_emit_literal" takes literal_ptr as Integer, literal_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a constant byte sequence to fd 2 via syscall_write. The
    "literal" must be a memory region the caller owns and has filled
    with bytes ahead of time. Used to emit the fixed prefix of the
    canary failure diagnostic.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single syscall_write(2, literal_ptr, literal_len).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Failure-path only.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes literal_len bytes to fd 2. Caller-supplied region; caller
    is responsible for the bytes.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, literal_ptr, literal_len
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_fail_abort" takes location_code as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer, expected_word_a as Integer, got_word_a as Integer, header_ptr as Integer, user_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminal failure handler for canary mismatches. Writes a
    fixed-format diagnostic to stderr (fd 2) and exits with code 134
    (= 128 + SIGABRT, mirrors how libc abort() terminates and matches
    AddressSanitizer's exit convention). Never returns.

    The diagnostic format is:
        CANARY FAILURE loc=N id=N gen=N exp=0x.. got=0x.. hdr=0x.. usr=0x..
    All values are emitted as 16-char hex (alloc_id, generation,
    expected, got, header_ptr, user_ptr) or single-digit ASCII for
    location_code. The format is fixed so external tooling can parse
    it without ambiguity.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate a small mmap'd "literal" region the first time (32
       bytes); reused via the canary_diag_scratch_ptr from
       canary_get_diag_scratch.
    2. Emit each literal segment via syscall_write inline (we manually
       build short byte sequences in-place to avoid needing a string
       table).
    3. Emit each hex value via canary_emit_hex_word.
    4. syscall_exit(134) - process terminates.

    Implementation uses repeated memory_set_byte to build the literal
    segments because pure-Runa primitives don't expose string-literal
    pointers to bytes; each segment is written byte-by-byte and then
    syscall_write'd.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Terminal path. Cost is irrelevant. Designed to be minimal-LOC
    rather than minimal-cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes attacker-readable bytes (alloc_id, generation, expected
    canary, observed canary, header pointer, user pointer) to fd 2.
    If stderr is attacker-readable this leaks the canary seed
    derivation evidence. Acceptable: at this point the process is
    already known to have been corrupted and will exit; the goal is
    diagnosability, not confidentiality.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let scratch be proc canary_get_diag_scratch
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Note: Cannot allocate scratch - direct exit, no diagnostic possible.
        proc syscall_exit from Syscall with 134
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Emit "CANARY FAILURE loc=" (19 bytes).
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 67    Note: 'C'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 78    Note: 'N'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 82    Note: 'R'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 5, 89    Note: 'Y'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 6, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 7, 70    Note: 'F'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 8, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 9, 73    Note: 'I'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 10, 76   Note: 'L'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 11, 85   Note: 'U'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 12, 82   Note: 'R'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 13, 69   Note: 'E'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 14, 32   Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 15, 108  Note: 'l'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 16, 111  Note: 'o'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 17, 99   Note: 'c'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 18, 61   Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 19

    Note: Emit location_code as a single ASCII digit (we have 5 codes; all single digit).
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, location_code plus 48
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 1

    Note: Emit " id=" prefix and the allocation id in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 105   Note: 'i'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 100   Note: 'd'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 4
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with alloc_id

    Note: Emit " gen=" prefix and generation in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 103   Note: 'g'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 101   Note: 'e'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 110   Note: 'n'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with generation

    Note: Emit " exp=" prefix and expected_word_a in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 101   Note: 'e'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 120   Note: 'x'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 112   Note: 'p'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with expected_word_a

    Note: Emit " got=" prefix and got_word_a in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 103   Note: 'g'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 111   Note: 'o'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 116   Note: 't'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with got_word_a

    Note: Emit " hdr=" prefix and header_ptr in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 104   Note: 'h'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 100   Note: 'd'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 114   Note: 'r'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with header_ptr

    Note: Emit " usr=" prefix and user_ptr in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 117   Note: 'u'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 115   Note: 's'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 114   Note: 'r'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with user_ptr

    Note: Emit trailing newline.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 10    Note: '\n'
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 1

    Note: Terminate process. Exit code 134 = 128 + SIGABRT, matching ASan.
    proc syscall_exit from Syscall with 134
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quarantine_init" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazily allocates the quarantine ring buffer the first time
    deallocate runs with DEBUG=1. The quarantine stores
    QUARANTINE_CAPACITY entries of QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE bytes each,
    backed by a single mmap region so the quarantine itself never
    competes with the heap registry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Check quarantine_initialized; if 1, return 1. Otherwise mmap
    (QUARANTINE_CAPACITY * QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE) bytes with
    PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, zero-fill,
    store the pointer, mark initialized.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-shot per program lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 2048 bytes outside the regular heap registry. The
    region is freed at program exit only.
    @End Security_Scope

    If quarantine_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let total_size be QUARANTINE_CAPACITY multiplied by QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let table_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If table_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with table_ptr, 0, total_size
    Set quarantine_table to table_ptr
    Set quarantine_head to 0
    Set quarantine_count to 0
    Set quarantine_initialized to 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "quarantine_push" takes user_ptr as Integer, total_size as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, alloc_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pushes a freshly-freed block onto the quarantine ring buffer.
    Returns the evicted entry's user_ptr (or 0 if no eviction
    happened yet). The caller is responsible for ACTUALLY freeing
    the evicted entry (munmap for mmap allocations, free-list-add
    for brk). This split lets deallocate keep its tier-specific
    finalization logic in deallocate itself; quarantine_push is a
    pure data-structure operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Entry layout (32 bytes):
       offset  0 -> user_ptr      (8 bytes)
       offset  8 -> total_size    (8 bytes)
       offset 16 -> alloc_id      (8 bytes)
       offset 24 -> alloc_type    (8 bytes)

    Steps:
     1. Ensure quarantine_init has run.
     2. Compute slot_ptr = quarantine_table + quarantine_head * 32.
     3. If quarantine_count == QUARANTINE_CAPACITY: read the OLD
        entry's user_ptr/total_size/alloc_id/alloc_type into out
        params and return user_ptr-of-old; we are EVICTING the slot.
     4. Otherwise return 0 (no eviction yet).
     5. Write the new entry at slot_ptr.
     6. quarantine_head = (quarantine_head + 1) mod QUARANTINE_CAPACITY.
     7. quarantine_count = min(quarantine_count + 1, QUARANTINE_CAPACITY).

    Since Runa primitives don't support out-params, we return only
    the evicted user_ptr; the eviction's total_size, alloc_id, and
    alloc_type are looked up via quarantine_get_evicted_*-style
    helpers OR cached in module-level slots written by this
    Process. Chosen approach: cache via module-level Let slots
    quarantine_last_evicted_total_size / _alloc_id / _alloc_type
    so the caller reads them right after quarantine_push returns
    nonzero. This avoids needing multi-return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) - one indexed write, three pointer updates. ~10 ns per
    push. The eviction case adds three more reads = ~14 ns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must verify user_ptr is currently owned by the allocator
    and has its canaries intact at the time of push. Quarantine
    does NOT re-verify on push; verification happens at eviction
    time inside quarantine_pop_evict_for_reuse.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let init_ok be proc quarantine_init
    If init_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head_offset be quarantine_head multiplied by QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let slot_ptr be quarantine_table plus head_offset
    Let evicted_user_ptr be 0
    If quarantine_count is greater than or equal to QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set evicted_user_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 0
        Let evicted_total_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 8
        Let evicted_alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 16
        Let evicted_alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 24
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_total_size to evicted_total_size
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_id to evicted_alloc_id
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_type to evicted_alloc_type
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 0, user_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 8, total_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 16, alloc_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 24, alloc_type
    Set quarantine_head to quarantine_head plus 1
    If quarantine_head is greater than or equal to QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set quarantine_head to 0
    End If
    If quarantine_count is less than QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set quarantine_count to quarantine_count plus 1
    End If
    Return evicted_user_ptr
End Process

Let quarantine_last_evicted_total_size be 0
Let quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_id be 0
Let quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_type be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation and Deallocation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "allocate" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tier 3 owned-heap allocator. Returns a pointer to USER DATA. The
    allocation header lives at ptr-header_size and contains four canonical
    fields at offsets 0/8/16/24 (allocation_id, generation, total_size,
    alloc_type). When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 1, the header
    is EXPANDED to 48 bytes: the canonical 32-byte field block is
    preserved bit-for-bit (B2 invariant) and a 16-byte per-allocation
    canary is appended at offsets 32 and 40. A second 16-byte canary is
    appended at ptr+aligned_size (the post-buffer canary). On
    deallocate() both canaries are verified; corruption aborts the
    process via canary_fail_abort. When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED
    is 0, header_size is 32 and no post-buffer canary is appended -
    behavior is identical to the B2-canonical layout.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute header_size = ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE + (DEBUG ?
       ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE : 0). Compute post_canary_size =
       (DEBUG ? ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE : 0).
    2. total_size = header_size + aligned_size + post_canary_size.
    3. Choose mmap (large) or brk (small) path identically to B2.
    4. Write the four canonical header fields at offsets 0/8/16/24.
    5. If DEBUG: write pre-canary at header_ptr+32 and post-canary at
       header_ptr+header_size+aligned_size (= user_ptr+aligned_size).
    6. For brk free-list reuse: verify the OLD pre-canary and
       post-canary BEFORE reusing the block; mismatch aborts via
       canary_fail_abort because that signals corruption inside a
       freed-but-quarantined region.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path. DEBUG=0 costs identical to B2 (zero canary work).
    DEBUG=1 adds ~30 ns/alloc for the canary writes and ~30 ns/free
    for the verifies. The free-list reuse path also incurs an
    additional verify on the OLD canary before overwriting; this
    catches use-after-free that wrote into the freed buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The header offsets 0/8/16/24 are a security boundary (per B2
    @Security_Scope on deallocate). The canary offsets 32/40 are a
    NEW security boundary: a canary write to the wrong place would
    overwrite the user buffer's first 16 bytes silently. Both write
    sites must use ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as the offset of the
    pre-canary relative to header_ptr.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Align size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8
    Note:
    Free-list reuse stores two 8-byte pointers (next, prev) in the
    user data area when this block is later deallocated. Ensure the
    user region is large enough to hold that metadata so the
    post-allocation is_free flag write at user_ptr+8 stays inside
    the allocated brk range. Without this floor a 2-byte allocation
    would only reserve 8 user bytes and the flag write would overflow
    into unmapped memory.
    :End Note
    If aligned_size is less than 16:
        Set aligned_size to 16
    End If

    Note: Compute header_size and post_canary_size at runtime so the
    Note: DEBUG=0 path collapses to the B2 layout. When DEBUG=0 the
    Note: If-blocks below are entered but write no canary bytes; the
    Note: arithmetic resolves to header_size=32 and post_canary_size=0.
    Let header_size be ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    Let post_canary_size be 0
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
        Set post_canary_size to ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let total_size be header_size plus aligned_size
    Set total_size to total_size plus post_canary_size

    Note: For small allocations, use brk
    Note: For large allocations (>128KB user data), use mmap
    Let threshold be 131072  Note: 128KB
    Let user_ptr be 0  Note: Will be set in either branch

    If aligned_size is greater than threshold:
        Note: Large allocation - use mmap
        Let prot be 3  Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
        Let flags be 34  Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
        Let header_ptr be proc syscall_mmap with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

        If header_ptr is less than 0:
            Return 0  Note: mmap failed
        End If

        Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
        Let alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id

        Note: Write canonical header metadata (B2 invariant)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0, alloc_id      Note: allocation_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8, 0             Note: generation = 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16, total_size   Note: size
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24, 2            Note: type = mmap

        Note: Calculate user data pointer
        Set user_ptr to header_ptr plus header_size

        Note: Write canaries (DEBUG=1 only). Pre-canary lives at the
        Note: byte immediately after the canonical 32-byte field block.
        Note: Post-canary lives immediately after the aligned user
        Note: buffer.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            proc canary_write_redzone with pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
            Let post_canary_ptr be user_ptr plus aligned_size
            proc canary_write_redzone with post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
        End If

        Note: Register allocation in registry
        Let reg_result be proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 2
        Note: If registry insert fails, allocation still succeeds but validation will not work

        Return user_ptr
    End If

    Note: Small allocation - check free list first
    Note: Initialize heap metadata if needed
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Let init_result be proc heap_init
        If init_result is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Failed to initialize heap
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try to find a free block that fits
    Let free_block be proc free_list_find_fit with total_size
    If free_block is not equal to 0:
        Note: Found a suitable free block - reuse it!
        Let dummy be proc free_list_remove_block with free_block
        Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_free_flag with free_block, 0

        Note: Get old allocation metadata from header
        Let free_block_header be free_block minus header_size
        Let old_alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 0
        Let old_generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 8

        Note: Verify the OLD canaries before reusing the block. A
        Note: mismatch here means the freed block was written to while
        Note: it sat on the free list or in quarantine - i.e., a
        Note: use-after-free that wrote bytes. Abort with diagnostic.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let old_pre_canary_ptr be free_block_header plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            Let pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with old_pre_canary_ptr, old_alloc_id, old_generation
            If pre_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with old_alloc_id, old_generation
                Let got_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_pre_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED, old_alloc_id, old_generation, exp_a, got_a, free_block_header, free_block
            End If
            Note: Post-canary location uses the OLD allocation's
            Note: total_size - we just read it as block_size below,
            Note: but the verify must happen before the registry
            Note: update overwrites anything. block_size is
            Note: header_size + aligned_user + post_canary_size, so
            Note: post canary sits at free_block + (block_size
            Note: - header_size - post_canary_size).
            Let old_block_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
            Let old_user_size be old_block_size minus header_size
            Set old_user_size to old_user_size minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
            Let old_post_canary_ptr be free_block plus old_user_size
            Let post_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with old_post_canary_ptr, old_alloc_id, old_generation
            If post_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_b be proc canary_seed_word_a with old_alloc_id, old_generation
                Let got_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_post_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_POST_OWNED, old_alloc_id, old_generation, exp_b, got_b, free_block_header, free_block
            End If
        End If

        Note: Remove old registry entry (address is being reused)
        proc registry_remove with old_alloc_id

        Note: Allocate new ID and increment generation for reuse
        Let new_alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id
        Let new_generation be old_generation plus 1

        Note: Update header with new metadata
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 0, new_alloc_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 8, new_generation

        Note: Re-stamp canaries with the new (alloc_id, generation)
        Note: so subsequent verifies use the fresh seed.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let new_pre_canary_ptr be free_block_header plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            proc canary_write_redzone with new_pre_canary_ptr, new_alloc_id, new_generation
            Let block_size_for_post be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
            Let user_size_for_post be block_size_for_post minus header_size
            Set user_size_for_post to user_size_for_post minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
            Let new_post_canary_ptr be free_block plus user_size_for_post
            proc canary_write_redzone with new_post_canary_ptr, new_alloc_id, new_generation
        End If

        Note: Register new allocation
        Let block_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
        Let user_size be block_size minus header_size
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Set user_size to user_size minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
        End If
        proc registry_insert with new_alloc_id, new_generation, free_block, user_size, 1

        Return free_block
    End If

    Note: No suitable free block - allocate new memory with brk
    Let current_brk be proc syscall_brk with 0
    Let new_brk be current_brk plus total_size
    Let result_brk be proc syscall_brk with new_brk

    If result_brk is less than new_brk:
        Return 0  Note: brk failed
    End If

    Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
    Set alloc_id to proc registry_allocate_id

    Note: Write canonical header metadata at current_brk (B2 invariant)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 0, alloc_id        Note: allocation_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 8, 0               Note: generation = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 16, total_size     Note: size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 24, 1              Note: type = brk

    Note: Calculate user data pointer
    Set user_ptr to current_brk plus header_size

    Note: Write canaries (DEBUG=1 only). Same layout as the mmap path.
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Let brk_pre_canary_ptr be current_brk plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
        proc canary_write_redzone with brk_pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
        Let brk_post_canary_ptr be user_ptr plus aligned_size
        proc canary_write_redzone with brk_post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize free flag (0 = allocated)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with user_ptr, 8, 0  Note: is_free = 0

    Note: Register allocation in registry
    proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 1

    Return user_ptr
End Process

Process called "deallocate" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases memory previously returned by allocate(). The owned-heap allocation
    header is 32 bytes and lives at ptr-32; its canonical layout is
    allocation_id at offset 0, generation at offset 8, total_size at offset 16,
    and alloc_type at offset 24. The reader here must mirror the writer in
    allocate() exactly or every owned-heap free reads garbage from user-data
    territory. The two arms (mmap vs brk) match the two write paths in
    allocate(): mmap returns memory to the kernel via munmap; brk allocations
    are placed on the per-process free list for reuse because brk cannot
    release individual blocks back to the kernel. Both arms increment the
    registry generation counter so any borrows still holding the old id
    observe the change on next validation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard (treat free(NULL) as a no-op success-ish return).
    2. Compute header_ptr = ptr - 32 (owned header size).
    3. Read header fields at the canonical offsets:
         offset 0  -> alloc_id    (8 bytes)
         offset 8  -> generation  (8 bytes, currently informational)
         offset 16 -> total_size  (8 bytes, header+aligned_user_size)
         offset 24 -> alloc_type  (8 bytes, 1=brk, 2=mmap)
    4. Mark the registry entry as not-alive so live borrow checks fail fast.
    5. For mmap allocations: bump the generation, syscall_munmap the full
       (header_ptr, total_size) region, drop the registry entry on success.
    6. For brk allocations: bump the generation and push ptr onto the
       free-list head via free_list_add_block. Registry entry is retained
       until the block is later reused, so generation/use-after-free checks
       continue to work on the freed block.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path is the brk branch (small allocations dominate compiler workload).
    free_list_add_block is O(1) LIFO; munmap on the mmap branch is a syscall
    and costs accordingly. Registry mutations are O(1) average via the
    open-addressed hash table in registry_lookup.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A header read at the wrong offset returns user-data bytes interpreted as
    a size and type, which would feed an attacker-controllable value into
    munmap. The offsets here are therefore a security boundary, not a
    correctness convenience.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL pointer (safe to ignore)
    End If

    Note: Get header pointer (32 bytes before user data for owned allocations)
    Let header_size be 32  Note: Owned allocation header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note:
    Read allocation metadata from header. Canonical owned-heap header layout
    (matches the writes in allocate()):
      offset 0  -> allocation_id
      offset 8  -> generation
      offset 16 -> total_size  (header + aligned user bytes)
      offset 24 -> alloc_type  (1=brk, 2=mmap)
    :End Note
    Let alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0
    Let generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8
    Let total_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24

    Note: Mark allocation as freed in registry (but keep entry for generation tracking)
    proc registry_update_alive with alloc_id, 0

    Note: Type 2 = mmap allocation (can be freed immediately)
    If alloc_type is equal to 2:
        Note: Increment generation for safety (in case address is reused by OS)
        proc registry_increment_generation with alloc_id

        Let result be proc syscall_munmap with header_ptr, total_size
        If result is equal to 0:
            Note: Successfully freed - remove from registry
            proc registry_remove with alloc_id
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0  Note: munmap failed
    End If

    Note: Type 1 = brk allocation - add to free list for reuse
    Note: Do NOT remove from registry - will be removed on reuse in allocate()
    Note: Just mark as freed and increment generation
    proc registry_increment_generation with alloc_id

    Let dummy be proc free_list_add_block with ptr
    Return 1  Note: Successfully added to free list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Variable Tracking (For Compiler Symbol Table)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Variable structure (32 bytes):
Note:   offset 0: name (string pointer)
Note:   offset 8: stack_offset (integer)
Note:   offset 16: type_name (string pointer)
Note:   offset 24: is_parameter (integer)

Process called "variable_create" takes name as String, stack_offset as Integer, type_name as String, is_parameter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create variable entry (Tier 3: Owned)

    Let var be proc allocate with 32
    If var is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_copy be proc string_duplicate with name
    proc memory_set_pointer with var, 0, name_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 with var, 8, stack_offset
    Let type_copy be proc string_duplicate with type_name
    proc memory_set_pointer with var, 16, type_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 with var, 24, is_parameter

    Return var
End Process

Process called "variable_destroy" takes var as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy variable entry

    If var is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name be proc memory_get_pointer with var, 0
    Let type_name be proc memory_get_pointer with var, 16

    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate with name
    End If

    If type_name is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate with type_name
    End If

    proc deallocate with var
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TIER 4: SHARED (Reference Counted)
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
Shared object header structure (prepended to each shared allocation):
offset -32: strong_refcount (atomic, 8 bytes) - counts strong references
offset -24: weak_refcount (atomic, 8 bytes) - counts weak references
offset -16: data_size (8 bytes) - size of user data
offset -8: allocation_type (8 bytes, 3=shared)
offset 0: user data begins here

Strong references keep the object alive.
Weak references allow checking if object is still alive without preventing deallocation.
When strong_refcount reaches 0, user data is freed but header remains for weak pointers.
When weak_refcount reaches 0, header is freed.
:End Note

Note:
Weak Pointer Structure (16 bytes):
offset 0: shared_header_ptr (pointer to shared object header, 8 bytes)
offset 8: is_valid (1 if target alive, 0 if deallocated, 8 bytes)
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Atomic Operations (REMOVED - Now use core/atomic_core.runa)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Atomic operations have been moved to core/atomic_core.runa
Note: Use Atomic.Atomic.atomic_increment(), Atomic.Atomic.atomic_decrement(), etc.

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Shared Object Creation and Reference Management
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "shared_create" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create shared object with initial refcount of 1
    Note: Returns pointer to USER DATA (header is hidden 32 bytes before it)
    Note: Must call shared_release() when done with this reference

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Align size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8
    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED: allocation_id (8) plus generation (8) plus strong_refcount (8) plus weak_refcount (8) plus data_size (8) plus allocation_type (8)
    Let total_size be header_size plus aligned_size

    Note: Always use mmap for shared allocations (can be unmapped independently)
    Let prot be 3  Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
    Let flags be 34  Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
    Let header_ptr be proc syscall_mmap with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If header_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0  Note: mmap failed
    End If

    Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
    Let alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id

    Note: Initialize header (NEW EXPANDED HEADER FOR SHARED)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0, alloc_id        Note: allocation_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8, 0               Note: generation = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16, 1              Note: strong_refcount = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24, 0              Note: weak_refcount = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32, aligned_size   Note: data_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40, 3              Note: allocation_type = 3 (shared)

    Note: Calculate user data pointer
    Let user_ptr be header_ptr plus header_size

    Note: Register allocation in registry
    proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 3

    Return user_ptr
End Process

Process called "shared_retain" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Increment reference count for shared object
    Note: Returns the same pointer (for convenience)
    Note: Returns 0 if ptr is NULL or invalid

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get header pointer
    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED shared header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation minus error!
    End If

    Note: Atomically increment strong refcount
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let new_count be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "shared_release" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Decrement reference count and free if zero
    Note: Returns 1 if object still alive, 0 if deallocated
    Note: Safe to call with NULL pointer (returns 0)

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get header pointer
    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED shared header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation minus error!
    End If

    Note: Atomically decrement strong refcount
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let new_count be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Note: If refcount reached 0, deallocate user data
    If new_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Weak pointers detect invalidity by checking strong_refcount = 0
        Note: No need to walk weak pointer list - they check atomically on access

        Note: Check if there are any weak references
        Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
        Let weak_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

        If weak_count is equal to 0:
            Note: No weak references - free entire allocation
            Let data_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32
            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
            proc syscall_munmap with header_ptr, total_size
            Return 0  Note: Object fully deallocated
        Otherwise:
            Note: Weak references exist - keep header, zero user data for safety
            Set data_size to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32
            proc memory_fill with ptr, 0, data_size
            Return 0  Note: Object deallocated (header remains for weak refs)
        End If
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Object still alive (refcount is greater than 0)
End Process

Process called "shared_get_refcount" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current strong reference count
    Note: Useful for debugging and testing
    Note: Returns 0 if ptr is NULL or invalid

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED shared header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Return proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Weak Pointer Support
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "weak_create" takes strong_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create weak pointer to shared object
    Note: Weak pointer does NOT increase strong refcount
    Note: Returns pointer to WeakPointer structure (16 bytes)
    Note: Must call weak_destroy() when done

    If strong_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED shared header
    Let header_ptr be strong_ptr minus header_size
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation
    End If

    Note: Allocate weak pointer structure
    Let weak_ptr be proc allocate with 16
    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Increment weak refcount on shared object
    Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
    Let dummy be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

    Note: Initialize weak pointer
    proc memory_set_pointer with weak_ptr, 0, header_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 1  Note: is_valid = 1

    Return weak_ptr
End Process

Process called "weak_lock" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Try to promote weak pointer to strong reference
    Note: Returns strong pointer if object still alive, 0 if deallocated
    Note: If successful, caller must eventually call shared_release()

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get shared object header
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0
    If header_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if object is still alive (strong_refcount > 0)
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    If strong_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Object has been deallocated
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0  Note: Mark weak pointer as invalid
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Object is alive - increment strong refcount
    Let new_count be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Note: Double-check it didn't get deallocated between load and increment
    If new_count is less than or equal to 1:
        Note: Race condition - object was being deallocated
        Note: Undo our increment
        Let dummy be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with refcount_ptr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Successfully promoted to strong reference
    Let header_size be 48  Note: EXPANDED shared header
    Let strong_ptr be header_ptr plus header_size
    Return strong_ptr
End Process

Process called "weak_destroy" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tears down a weak pointer to a shared/ARC object. The weak pointer holds
    a back-reference to the shared header (48 bytes). When the last weak
    reference goes away AND the strong refcount has already hit zero, the
    header itself is reclaimed; otherwise the header stays alive so other
    weak pointers can still observe the strong_count=0 state and report
    invalidation. The shared header layout is allocation_id at 0,
    generation at 8, strong_refcount at 16, weak_refcount at 24, data_size
    at 32, allocation_type at 40 - this routine must read those offsets
    exactly, since misreading either field corrupts the final munmap call.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Load the shared header pointer cached at weak_ptr+0.
    3. Atomically decrement weak_refcount at header+24.
    4. If weak_refcount has reached 0, load strong_refcount from header+16
       (NOT from header+0 which is the allocation_id) to decide whether
       the header is finally reclaimable.
    5. If both counts are zero, read alloc_type at header+40 and data_size
       at header+32 (these are positionally swapped relative to the
       owned-heap header; the shared header reverses them). Today shared
       objects always come from mmap, so only the ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP arm
       fires in practice, but all four arms are kept structurally to allow
       future shared-from-arena / shared-from-brk extensions to slot in
       without revisiting this finalizer.
    6. munmap (header_ptr, 48 + data_size).
    7. Free the weak-pointer structure itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path (only fires when both strong and weak counts hit zero in
    succession). The atomic_decrement on weak_refcount is the only fast
    operation; the conditional munmap is amortized across the lifetime of
    the shared object.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same boundary as deallocate(): reading the wrong offset from the
    header would feed attacker-controllable bytes into munmap. The
    refcount/offset reads must mirror shared_create() exactly.
    @End Security_Scope

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get shared object header
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0

    If header_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Note: Decrement weak refcount
        Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
        Let new_weak_count be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

        Note: If both strong and weak counts are 0, free header
        If new_weak_count is equal to 0:
            Note:
            Read strong_refcount from its canonical offset (header+16).
            The previous implementation read header+0 here, which is the
            allocation_id field, not the refcount - so the strong-count
            test was effectively checking whether the allocation_id was
            zero, which can never happen since IDs start at 1. That
            caused this finalizer to leak the header every time the
            data-only release path in shared_release() had already
            happened.
            :End Note
            Let strong_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16
            Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with strong_refcount_ptr

            If strong_count is equal to 0:
                Note:
                Read allocation metadata from the shared header.
                Shared header layout (48 bytes):
                  offset 0  -> allocation_id
                  offset 8  -> generation
                  offset 16 -> strong_refcount
                  offset 24 -> weak_refcount
                  offset 32 -> data_size
                  offset 40 -> allocation_type
                The previous implementation swapped the offsets for
                alloc_method and data_size, which made alloc_method
                resolve to the user-supplied data_size (almost always a
                nonzero non-method value) and skipped every branch of
                the dispatch, leaking the header.
                :End Note
                Let data_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32
                Let alloc_method be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40

                Note: Free based on allocation method
                If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP:
                    If data_size is greater than 0:
                        If data_size is less than 1073741824:
                            Let header_size be 48
                            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
                            proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with header_ptr, total_size
                        End If
                    End If
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED:
                    Note:
                    Shared header tagged with ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED (=3).
                    shared_create() writes 3 at offset 40, so the
                    common case actually falls here, not into the MMAP
                    arm. Shared objects always come from mmap (see
                    shared_create), so reclamation goes through munmap
                    on the full (header + data_size) span.
                    :End Note
                    If data_size is greater than 0:
                        If data_size is less than 1073741824:
                            Let header_size be 48
                            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
                            proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with header_ptr, total_size
                        End If
                    End If
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_BRK:
                    Note: brk-allocated shared objects are not produced today;
                    Note: this arm exists so future brk-backed shared variants
                    Note: have a place to plug in. brk cannot free individual
                    Note: blocks, so the header would have to be parked on
                    Note: the owned-heap free list - that mechanism is
                    Note: deliberately not invoked here to avoid mixing tiers.
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_ARENA:
                    Note: Arena-backed shared objects are not produced today;
                    Note: arena bulk-frees its entire buffer on arena_destroy,
                    Note: so per-object reclamation is intentionally a no-op.
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Free weak pointer structure itself
    proc deallocate with weak_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "weak_is_valid" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if weak pointer still points to live object
    Note: Returns 1 if alive, 0 if deallocated or invalid

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check cached validity flag first
    Let is_valid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Already known to be invalid
    End If

    Note: Check actual strong refcount
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0
    If header_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    If strong_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Object has been deallocated - update cache
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Object is still alive
End Process

